**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:

When using the [CSV processor](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/csv-processor.html) with `\t` (tab) delimited log files, such as this one, it errors while testing the processor.

```
"2020-01-05 08:14:13.001Z"	INFO	ThreadName	"My really cool log message"	
```

Originally, I _thought_ I experienced the failure when creating the ingest pipeline with an error about only a single character is allowed as the separator, which is covered by https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/issues/55075.  But I tried reproducing it in 7.10.1, 7.9.3, and 7.8.1 and all of them create the pipeline now.  So I'm going to guess it was my end user error. 

**Steps to reproduce**:

1. Create the pipeline

    ```
    PUT _ingest/pipeline/csv_ingest_example
    {
      "processors": [
        {
          "csv": {
            "field": "event.original",
            "separator": "\t",
            "target_fields": [
            "@timestamp",
            "log.level",
            "process.thread.name",
            "message"
            ]
          }
        }
      ]
    }
    ```

2. Test the ingest pipeline

    ```
    POST _ingest/pipeline/csv_ingest_example/_simulate
    {
      "docs": [
        {
          "_source": {
            "event": {
              "original": """"2020-01-05 08:14:13.001Z"	INFO	ThreadName	"My really cool log message"	"""
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    }

    POST _ingest/pipeline/csv_ingest_example/_simulate
    {
      "docs": [
        {
          "_source": {
            "event": {
              "original": "\"2020-01-05 08:14:13.001Z\"\tINFO\tThreadName\t\"My really cool log message\"\t"
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    }
    ```

The error from both of the above `_simulate` commands

```json
    {
      "docs" : [
        {
          "error" : {
            "root_cause" : [
              {
                "type" : "illegal_argument_exception",
                "reason" : "character 'I' after quoted field at 27"
              }
            ],
            "type" : "illegal_argument_exception",
            "reason" : "character 'I' after quoted field at 27"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
```

**Provide logs (if relevant)**: I didn't see anything related to the above error message

**Work Around**: I was able to work around the problem by changing the pipeline to this based on https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/issues/55075#issuecomment-612141615

```
PUT _ingest/pipeline/csv_ingest_example
{
  "processors": [
    {
      "dissect": {
        "field": "event.original",
        "pattern": "\"%{@timestamp}\"\t%{_ingest.msg}"
      }
    },
    {
      "gsub": {
        "field": "_ingest.msg",
        "pattern": "\t",
        "replacement": "|"
      }
    },
    {
      "csv": {
        "field": "_ingest.msg",
        "separator": "|",
        "target_fields": [
          "log.level",
          "process.thread.name",
          "message"
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

This also worked, so maybe it is the case that it does not like the first element in the record to be quoted?

```
PUT _ingest/pipeline/csv_ingest_example
{
  "processors": [
    {
      "dissect": {
        "field": "event.original",
        "pattern": "\"%{@timestamp}\"\t%{_ingest.msg}"
      }
    },
    {
      "csv": {
        "field": "_ingest.msg",
        "separator": "\t",
        "target_fields": [
          "log.level",
          "process.thread.name",
          "message"
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

